30
00:01:48.790 --> 00:01:52.080
Given how important databases are in
today's business environment,

31
00:01:52.080 --> 00:01:56.230
it is crucial to understand how
data is stored in these databases.

32
00:01:56.230 --> 00:01:59.449
The concept of a data model
is key to understanding this.

33
00:02:00.900 --> 00:02:03.000
Let's take a look at data models.

34
00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:04.640
What is a data model?

35
00:02:04.640 --> 00:02:07.210
And how might a data model
function within a database?

36
00:02:08.290 --> 00:02:12.670
A data model will tell us what data can
be stored, where it can be stored, and

37
00:02:12.670 --> 00:02:14.450
how to store the data.

38
00:02:14.450 --> 00:02:17.090
It will also prevent bad data
from entering the database.

39
00:02:18.290 --> 00:02:22.050
A data model states the rules under
which the database will operate.

40
00:02:22.050 --> 00:02:26.000
Other places where you might have
heard of a data model is in XML.

41
00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:28.110
XML uses a hierarchical data model,

42
00:02:28.110 --> 00:02:32.140
which means that data is stored in such
a manner that it looks like a tree.

43
00:02:32.140 --> 00:02:33.770
Every tree has branches.

44
00:02:33.770 --> 00:02:35.080
And every branch has leaves.

45
00:02:36.340 --> 00:02:39.390
Relational data bases use
a relational data model.

46
00:02:39.390 --> 00:02:43.960
This means that the data is stored in
rows rather than in tree like structures.

47
00:02:43.960 --> 00:02:47.730
Finally, why is relational
data useful in today's world?

48
00:02:47.730 --> 00:02:51.380
Relational data allows for
tables to connect and share data.

49
00:02:51.380 --> 00:02:54.700
Using this model, duplicate data will
not be collected because data is

50
00:02:54.700 --> 00:02:56.870
typically only stored once
in a relational model.

51
00:02:56.870 --> 00:03:02.330
You can relate one row of data
to many other rows of data.

52
00:03:02.330 --> 00:03:06.900
In other models, that one row of data
will have to be repeated many times.

53
00:03:06.900 --> 00:03:10.383
This matters when a database becomes
large because maintaining it will be more

54
00:03:10.383 --> 00:03:11.930
difficult.

55
00:03:11.930 --> 00:03:15.410
Relational databases strive to
keep the database size smaller and

56
00:03:15.410 --> 00:03:17.570
prevent duplicate rows of data.

